Introduction

The goal of this analysis is to understand the spatial relationships and crime. The data consists of arrestsper 100,000 residents for assault, murder, and rape in each of the 50 US states in 1973. Thus, we are using panel data for this analysis. The main tool used in this review of the data is cluster analysis. There are severalalgorithms deployed here to review relationship. The first tool is hierarchical clustering using both agglomerative and divisive modeling. This analysis is followed by secondary clusering using k-means clustering and k-medoids to add further robustness to the analysis.

Cluster Selection

In order to begin the analysis, there needs to be testing of the data to understand what is considered a reasonable amount of clusters to use. The first graph here is using the elbow method. This method minimizes within-cluster variation as the criteria for selection. The second graph uses silhouette analysis to determine clusters. Instead of within-cluster varation, it uses the average distance of each point in a cluster is to the nearest neighboring cluster. This allows for for the selection of well-defined clustered. Lastly, the gap statistic is used. The gap statistic reviews the relationship of the total within intra-cluster variation and its expection by essentially using hypothesis testing. The goal is to see if the formation of clusters are statistically different from a random uniform distribution and to maximize GAP statistic. Through reviewing these selection critea, using three clusters seems reasonable. This is supported by the GAP statistic. As the GAP statistic is a statistical test, it should hold more signficant in modeling than compared to more holestic analysis.

Method Selection

The first method being evaluated is aggregate hierarchical clustering. There are several methods considered to implement this clustering procedure. The complete method calculates dissimilarity between all the points of a cluster and all the points of the other and finds the maximize. Likewise, single link clusterings uses the smallest of these values, while averages linkage uses the mean dissimilarity. Walds method minimizes variance of within cluster variation and mininmized between-cluster varation with pairs. The agglomerative coefficient is a tool that determines the strength of clusters and was used to make the determination of which method to apply.

This dendrogram enables us to see the larger picuture. Through aggreation, it high likes features that are common between sets. It appears that population is one of the more signficant factors. For instance, North Dakota, Maine, Iowa, and New Hampshire are clustered together. Those states are sparsely populated and filled with wilderness. The states that are more dangerous and are more populated seem to be more rightward. New York and Texas are part of the same for example.

Using Partition Around Medoids

Lastly, k-medoids were implemented. The main reason for doing so is for a robustness check. The overall structure of the clusters is anaglous to kmeans. Because K-medoids minimizes the summation of pairwise dissimilarities for its criteria, it is less biased due to the presense of outliers in the data.
